<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="87" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="87">
An uncommon species of moist to wet soil in the subantarctic moorlands and 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Nothofagaceae" genus="Nothofagus" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Nothofagus" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Nothofagus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forests in southern Chile, reaching north to the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Aisén">Aisen</normalizedToken>
Region (
<bibRefCitation author="Ochi, H" journalOrPublisher="Nature and Science" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" pagination="11 - 47" refId="B18" refString="Ochi, H, 1982. A revision of the Bryoideae (Musci) in southern South America. Journal of the Faculty of Education, Tottori University. Nature and Science 31: 11 - 47" title="A revision of the Bryoideae (Musci) in southern South America. Journal of the Faculty of Education, Tottori University." volume="31" year="1982">Ochi 1982</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/phytokeys.68.9181" author="Larrain, J" journalOrPublisher="PhytoKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" pagination="91 - 116" refId="B8" refString="Larrain, J, 2016. The mosses (Bryophyta) of Capitan Prat Province, Aisen Region, southern Chile. PhytoKeys 68: 91 - 116, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/phytokeys.68.9181" title="The mosses (Bryophyta) of Capitan Prat Province, Aisen Region, southern Chile." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/phytokeys.68.9181" volume="68" year="2016">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Larraín">Larrain</normalizedToken>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
)). The species is characterized by dioicous sexual condition, rosulate stems, large ovate leaves that are 
<normalizedToken originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
imbricate when dry, costa excurrent into a short awn, a fairly well developed limbidium, finely serrulate distal leaf margins, and brown to red-brown rhizoidal tubers. The species is also known from the Falkland Islands and Argentina (Illustrations: 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1093/nq/14-1-36" author="Ochi, H" journalOrPublisher="Hikobia" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" pagination="14 - 36" refId="B15" refString="Ochi, H, 1967. Notes on moss flora V. Hikobia 5: 14 - 36, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1093/nq/14-1-36" title="Notes on moss flora V." url="https://doi.org/10.1093/nq/14-1-36" volume="5" year="1967">Ochi 1967</bibRefCitation>
: 33, as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cardot &amp; Brotherus" authorityYear="1923" class="Bryopsida" family="Bryaceae" genus="Bryum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Bryum macrophyllum" order="Bryales" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="species" species="macrophyllum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Bryum macrophyllum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
